  "prompt": "What does it mean when ETA case number shows \"Certified\" in iCERT?",
  "response": "When an ETA case number shows \"Certified\" in iCERT (the online portal for the Department of Labor's Office of Foreign Labor Certification), it means the labor certification application associated with that case number has been approved.\n\nHere's a breakdown of what that signifies:\n\n*   **Approval of the Labor Certification:** The Department of Labor (DOL) has reviewed the application and determined that the employer has met the requirements for obtaining a labor certification. This typically means the DOL has found that:\n    *   The employer has sufficiently advertised the job opportunity and made a good-faith effort to recruit U.S. workers.\n    *   There are not sufficient U.S. workers who are able, willing, qualified, and available to perform the job.\n    *   Employing the foreign worker will not adversely affect the wages and working conditions of similarly employed U.S. workers.\n\n*   **Next Steps for the Employer and Foreign Worker:** A certified labor certification is a crucial step in the green card process for employment-based immigration. With the \"Certified\" status, the employer (or sometimes the foreign worker, depending on the visa category) can now proceed to the next stage:\n\n    *   **Filing an Immigrant Petition (Form I-140) with USCIS:** The employer typically files Form I-140, Petition for Alien Worker, with U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS). The certified labor certification is a required document to support the I-140 petition.\n\n    *   **Applying for an Immigrant Visa or Adjustment of Status:** Once the I-140 is approved, the foreign worker can then apply for an immigrant visa at a U.S. embassy or consulate abroad (if they are outside the U.S.) or apply for adjustment of status to permanent resident (green card) if they are already in the U.S. and eligible.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **It's not a guarantee of a green card:** A \"Certified\" labor certification is an important step, but it does not automatically guarantee that the foreign worker will receive a green card. USCIS still needs to approve the I-140 petition and the immigrant visa application/adjustment of status application.\n*   **Priority Dates and Visa Availability:** The foreign worker's ability to proceed to the I-140 and immigrant visa/adjustment of status stages depends on their \"priority date.\" The priority date is generally the date the labor certification application was filed (or in some cases, the date the I-140 petition was filed).  Due to annual limits on the number of employment-based green cards available, there can be significant wait times depending on the foreign worker's country of origin and the employment-based visa category.\n*   **Expiration:** Labor certifications can expire if an I-140 is not filed within a certain timeframe.\n*   **Review the Details:** Always carefully review the details of the certified labor certification to ensure accuracy, as errors could cause issues later in the immigration process.\n\nIn summary, \"Certified\" in iCERT is a positive sign, indicating that the labor certification has been approved by the DOL, paving the way for the next steps in the employment-based green card process.\n",
